modules. There is no speed difference between most modern swerve modules, the things that determine speed are motors and gearings.</p>","post_number":4,"post_type":1,"posts_count":10,"updated_at":"2024-07-05T15:46:21.600Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":3,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":385,"readers_count":384,"score":127.0,"yours":false,"topic_id":468343,"topic_slug":"do-you-replace-youre-swerve-once-in-a-while","display_username":"Eliot Dunn","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","reply_to_user":{"id":63061,"username":"The_big_Melon","name":"Eilon nave huppert","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/the_big_melon/{size}/236259_2.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[{"id":2,"count":3}],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":52966,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"111 Alum"},"post_url":"/t/do-you-replace-youre-swerve-once-in-a-while/468343/4","custom_user_title":"111 Alum","reactions":[{"id":"heart","type":"emoji","count":3}],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":3,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3405531,"name":"Mr. Siefen | 453","username":"kingc95","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/kingc95/{size}/226662_2.png","created_at":"2024-07-05T16:09:59.555Z","cooked":"<p>And also programming settings. We used the High Speed gearing and a Neo for drive, neo 550 to steer. At full speed our drivers had trouble maintaining control. So artificially we had 3 speed modes adjusted by the driver at the drive station. Low was used for training, mid was used for most matches, high was hardly ever used.</p>
